>>31318107
It's not in the Bible directly. Due to some language barriers certain groups thought that Saint Christopher was a dog man (cynocephalus) which sparked debate among religious scholars and the like about whether a race of dog people or animal people would be considered as equals to man in the eyes of Christ. Most notably, Saint Augustine wrote about animal people in "The City of God" and came to the conclusion that were a race of these animal people to exist then so long as they were a mortal and rational animal that they would be considered human just the same as all of us and thus equals under God and also descendants of Adam. That's also something interesting to note- how to be "human" was not any certain physical makeup but instead dependent moreso on intellectual capacity. In a world of anthros humans as we know them would probably be called something completely different.
